<p>Autosomal dominant osteopetrosis type II is characterized by sclerosis, predominantly involving the spine, the pelvis, and the skull base. Fragility of bones and dental abscess are leading complications.</p>

<p>Autosomal dominant osteopetrosis type I (OPTA1;) is characterized by generalized osteosclerosis most pronounced in the cranial vault. Patients are often asymptomatic, but some suffer from pain and hearing loss. It appears to be the only type of osteopetrosis not associated with an increased fracture rate.</p>